**Lexical extraction model for enhanced temporal period classification of historical texts**

Liam V. Sullivan

**Historians often face the difficult and time-consuming task of classifying documents into the time period in which they were written, a process known as text dating. Methods of automating this task have been created, but often struggle with documents that are about a time different than the one they were written in. This research used an inverse tf-idf statistic to generate profiles of each time period represented by a group of training documents, which was then used to mask documents by removing the least significant features of each document. Training documents were then inputted into BERT, which generated a high-dimensional vector from its pooler output. Vector representations were used to train an SVM, which was then used to classify similarly transformed testing documents. Accuracy was assessed using three metrics to quantify deviance between estimated and correct time periods. Average raw accuracy was found to be within 25% of the baseline, and no statistical significance was found between most tests. It is concluded that the proposed lexical extraction does not significantly improve accuracy, but could potentially be adjusted to positively impact the accuracy of text dating models.**

**Keywords:** *text dating, feature representation, SVMs, tf-idf*

The date or period in which a document was written is incredibly important to historians to learn more about that time and the society that the work was a part of, as well as assisting in preservation of these documents and their context. However, the process of classifying documents into time periods, often known as text dating, can be difficult and time-consuming. Because of this, many historians would benefit from a more efficient solution, and consequently, artificial intelligence classification models can be employed by historians as aids to provide them with estimates of a time when a text might have been written.  
The natural language processing (NLP) subfield of artificial intelligence aims to use machine learning to aid in tasks such as these which require a large amount of information to be processed and historical context to be known. In order to allow the model to “read” texts, algorithms such as tokenizers and transformers must be used in combination to convert text into vectors that can be interpreted and compared by the computer. This process is known as feature representation. However, the model does not “understand” these representations as words with meaning by themselves, and can only use them in comparison to other data. To model historical trends that the inputted text can be compared against to estimate the time in which it was written, a collection of texts with known timestamps is required by NLP algorithms. This collection is known as training data.  
Given the usefulness of text dating tools and the considerable amount of time that NLP models have existed, a significant amount of research has already been done. Models have been trained to use names of events and people to assign a date to a text (Dalli & Wilks, 2006; Kumar et al., 2011; Toner & Han, 2019), compare the appearance of different topics among recent years (Abe & Tsumoto, 2010), and even recognize how the meaning of different words shift over time (Ren et al., 2023). In the past, these models have been used to accomplish tasks such as guessing temporal information about many types of texts. Their capability to reach high levels of accuracy has been repeatedly proven, with an accuracy of over 87% in one instance (Dalli & Wilks, 2006). Research done more recently trained a model to date medieval Irish and English documents, with accuracy ranging up to around 60% for certain time periods and types of texts (Toner & Han, 2019). Significant success has also been shown by ordering documents in chronological order relative to each other rather than predicting an absolute creation date for each document (Niculae et al., 2014).  
The utility and accuracy of these models has increased over the years, but weaknesses are still present. One example is that many of these models use specific named entities—such as places, people, and events—to help determine the age of a text, using the expectation that they can be correctly associated with other texts of which the creation dates are known. While this may be true in some cases, such as newspaper articles, where the documents write mainly about then-current events, it is significantly less reliable when dealing with historical records and descriptions of times other than the time a document was written in as the model is likely operating on the assumption that the appearance of certain topics is an accurate predictor of the date of writing (Kanhabua & Nørvåg, 2008; Toner & Han, 2019). These documents were considered the “target documents” of this research and are defined as documents that are primarily about a period other than the one they were written in. The objective of this research was to increase accuracy for these documents over existing basic methods by creating a machine learning model that was able to isolate specific features from language more descriptive of the time period each document belongs to, using that data to create a profile of each time period and comparing testing data against these profiles to match them to a period and make a prediction on their date of writing.  
Research already conducted on this topic has employed a variety of methods to process text data. One widely used strategy is the use of *n*\-grams, which are sequences of *n* consecutive terms (generally words or characters). For optimization purposes, *n* is often set to equal one, two, or three. The use of *n*\-grams to represent features of documents often yields accurate results (Boldsen & Wahlberg, 2021; Garcia-Fernandez et al., 2011; Tian & Kübler, 2021; Toner & Han, 2019). However, other methods such as the use of transformer algorithms has been shown to be more effective (Tian & Kübler, 2021). Transformers such as Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers (BERT) (Devlin et al., 2018\) tokenize data by separating the root of each word and any additional information. Each piece of information is referred to as a “token.” Each token is assigned a numerical value and is inputted into an algorithm that returns a vector representation of the set of tokens. This is done in such a way that vectors can be compared against each other, and similar vectors represent text with similar meanings. Many transformers are commonly used in NLP applications, such as BERT, RoBERTa (Liu et al., 2019), Sentence-BERT (Reimers & Gurevych, 2019\) and Longformer (Beltagy et al., 2020), each of which specialize in different tasks.  
Previous text dating research has often used support vector machines (SVMs) to classify documents into time periods. SVMs are machine learning algorithms that find hyperplanes to separate data in multidimensional space, enabling classification of new data by its placement into the existing, categorized multidimensional space. This is often applied to the high-dimensional vectors outputted by transformer models. SVMs have been shown to be effective tools that often perform better than other classification algorithms for this task (Boldsen & Wahlberg, 2021; Garcia-Fernandez et al., 2011; Liebeskind & Liebeskind, 2020; Niculae et al., 2014; Tian & Kübler, 2021\) This research uses the LinearSVC class from scikit-learn (Pedregosa et al., 2011), which allows the implementation of an SVM using a linear kernel, resulting in lower computational demand and faster training time.  
This research used BERT from the Hugging Face Transformers library (Wolf et al., 2020\) to tokenize a set of training documents separated by the decade they were written in. The base uncased version of the model was used in this experiment. Documents from each 10-year period within the training data were then analyzed to generate a profile of the period, and testing documents were compared against each period using an SVM in order to determine the closest match. Accuracy was assessed based on three statistics measuring differing levels of deviation from the correct period.

**Methods**  
To ensure a dataset of adequate quality, documents were sourced from four different online sources—the Internet Archive, the UNESCO International Bureau of Education, the Text Creation Partnership based at the University of Michigan, and the HathiTrust Digital Library—that provide historical documents converted to plain text files. Only documents written primarily in English between the years of 1800 and 2009 were selected. Documents were filtered to those with a historical subject to ensure they fit the target document criteria. Documents were then organized by time period, and a set of working files was isolated using a maximum of 150 documents from each 10-year time period 1800-2009.

![][image1]  
**Fig. 1\.** Diagram of the model framework. Documents are separated into training and testing groups, and training documents are separated by creation period. Within each time period, documents are analyzed using inverse tf-idf and masked according to the top most significant tokens that make up their corresponding time period. These masked documents are fed into the transformer model and the SVM is trained on the outputs. Testing documents are also passed through the transformer model and classified using the previously trained SVM. Accuracy is assessed based on *Acc*, *Acc@3*, and *Acc@5*.

***Document Chunking and Tokenization***  
In order to make documents more usable, documents were separated into chunks by paragraph, assuming each paragraph was separated by a blank line. This separation allowed documents to take up less memory and processing power than if they were considered in one piece. Additionally, BERT limits inputs to 512 tokens each, which corresponds to even fewer words per chunk, so using entire documents as input was not feasible.  
Following chunking, documents were inputted into BertTokenizerFast, a tokenizer associated with BERT. Strings of text that did not include word characters (defined as alphanumeric characters and underscores) were assumed to likely be improperly digitized and converted into an “\[UNK\]” token, which is used by BERT to represent an unknown word and is handled as one that carries no meaning. Tokenized documents were organized by time period.

***Profile Generation***  
To determine the defining characteristics of each time period, the term frequency–inverse document frequency (tf-idf) statistic was used: 

tf*\-*idf(t, c, C)=tf(t, c)idf(t, C)

where tf(t, c) is the relative frequency of term t within chunk c (the fraction of all terms in the chunk that are term t), and idf(t, C) is the logarithmically scaled inverse fraction of the chunks that contain term t within the set of all chunks C:

idf(t, C)=logNdf(t)

where df(t) is the number of chunks that contain term t. The use of this statistic was implemented using scikit-learn’s TfidfVectorizer. Resulting tf-idf values were ordered in descending order and scaled such that the minimum value was one. These values were adjusted according to the normal distribution of the set of whole numbers, starting at zero, with the same size as the set of tf-idf values in order to add weight to the middle-ranked values. Values were re-sorted and the upper quantile, of a different fraction for each test, was identified and removed from the data. The resulting profile was saved and the process was repeated for each time period in the training data.

***Transformation and SVM Training***  
To prepare for transformation, a mask was generated for each chunk according to its period’s profile. A mask serves to direct the transformer to ignore certain inputted tokens, which correspond to a zero in the mask. Each token in the chunk was given a corresponding value in a mask, where a zero represented its absence in the profile (and therefore its removal due to the removal of the profile’s upper quartile) and a one represented the token’s presence in the profile.   
After generating masks for each chunk in each time period, all tokenized chunks and masks were adjusted to a length of 512 to match the input size limit of the BERT model. This was done either by truncation or by appending zeros to both the list of tokens and its mask to ensure the added values would not be considered in transformation. The model was trained on an NVIDIA GeForce RTX 3060 Laptop GPU. The training was done in batches of 128 chunks to ensure the allotted 6 GB of GPU memory would not be exceeded. The training data was shuffled to ensure each batch would be composed of chunks from randomly selected periods, rather than all from one decade. Each batch of 128 chunk-mask pairs was passed into the BERT model, and the model’s pooler output for each chunk was taken and saved as a representation of the chunk. All outputs and their period of writing were saved.  
After the transformation of all chunks was completed, all chunks and their creation dates were inputted into scikit-learn’s LinearSVC, configured with a maximum iteration limit of 108.

***Testing and Accuracy Evaluation***  
Similar to the training data, all testing documents were chunked, tokenized, and transformed, with the exception that no profiles were generated and no tokens were removed. A full mask containing all ones was created for each chunk, and the length of each chunk and mask was adjusted to a length of 512 in the same manner as the training data. All chunks were fed into the previously trained SVM, and an estimate of the creation period was obtained.  
Following Ren et al. (2023), documents were assessed based on *Acc@K*, defined as:

Acc@K=Nacc@KNall

where *Nacc@K* is the number of testing documents dated within the adjacent ⌊K2⌋ periods to the correct one, and *Nall* is the total number of testing documents. This model was assessed using *Acc* (evaluating only documents dated to the correct time period), *Acc@3*, and *Acc@5*. This allowed for a more flexible interpretation of the accuracy of the model, and a greater understanding of its behavior.

**Results**  
Accuracy measurements ranged from roughly 0.13-0.20 for *Acc* measurements, 0.29-0.40 for *Acc@3* measurements, and 0.42-0.54 for *Acc@5* measurements. The statistical significance of each test was analyzed using the standard error of the mean (SEM), the results of which are shown in *Table 1*. *Fig. 2* shows a bar graph of this data. Confusion matrices were generated for each test, as shown in *Fig. 3*. This helped to visualize the accuracy of each model in regard to each specific time period and identify periods that could potentially pose greater difficulty and result in lower accuracy across multiple tests, as well as visualize the accuracy of each model in a more easily understandable way.

**Table 1\.** Average accuracy measurements (± SEM) of the model with different amounts removed. No statistically significant difference was found between the *Acc* measurements with 0.0625 and 0.125 removed, and the *Acc@3* and *Acc@5* measurements with 0.0625, 0.125, and 0.25 removed. BASE represents the baseline test.

**Fig. 2\.** A bar graph showing the average accuracy measurements (± SEM) of the model with different amounts removed. Average accuracy measurements (± SEM) of the model with different amounts removed. No statistically significant difference was found between the *Acc* measurements with 0.0625 and 0.125 removed, and the *Acc@3* and *Acc@5* measurements with 0.0625, 0.125, and 0.25 removed. BASE represents the baseline test. A slight trend suggesting an increase in accuracy can be seen as the removal ratio approaches 0.125 and a decrease in accuracy past that point, but no statistically significant change can be measured.  
**Fig. 3\.** Confusion matrices of each test group, by removal ratio. The frequency of each potential combination of predicted time period and actual time period is shown as a ratio of all testing documents that are described by that combination. Most matrices show a trend along the diagonal, suggesting a trend of accurate predictions. The test group with a 0.5 removal ratio shows mostly vertical lines, suggesting that many documents were predicted to belong to a few time periods.

**Discussion**  
Due to the overlap of SEM values, it was determined that there was no statistically significant difference from the baseline and the *Acc* measurements of the tests with 0.0625 and 0.125 removal ratios and the *Acc@3* and *Acc@5*  measurements of the tests with 0.0625, 0.125, and 0.25 removal ratios. Because of this, it was concluded that the lexical extraction model was not an effective change to text dating algorithms in its current state, however, it also did not remove data important to the period classification process with the exception of the 0.5 removal ratio test. This may be because, in most cases, the transformer model was able to generate roughly the same vector representation without the presence of the tokens weighted highest by the inverse tf-idf statistic, leading to a lack of considerable difference in the training of the SVM and a similar accuracy measurement.   
Alternatively, the removal of the the top weighted tokens by inverse tf-idf may not be a suitable way to generate a profile of each time period. The removal of the bottom quartile of weighed tokens, as well as the removal of both the top and bottom quartiles, was not considered in this research. Further investigation is required to determine if these methods would produce a more accurate model.  
Additionally, it is unknown how the lexical extraction model described in this research would interact with other algorithms in use by existing text dating models. Because of the variation in the architecture of different machine learning algorithms such as tokenizers, transformers, and classifiers, the use of different algorithms within the model could result in a change in measured accuracy. For example, the use of a BERT derivative such as RoBERTa or Sentence-BERT may affect how documents are represented, and can therefore change the effect of the lexical extraction model on the accuracy of their classification. (Ren et al., 2023\) The use of *n*\-grams can also result in a change in performance (Tian & Kübler, 2021).  Different classification algorithms may also handle the data generated by lexical extraction differently. Using an SVM with a different kernel, such as polynomial or radial basis function rather than linear, would likely result in an increase in accuracy due to the more complex hyperplane generation method, albeit at the cost of increased computational demand.  
Due to the loss of information inherent to the removal of the top quartile of each periods’ weights, the lexical extraction model may especially benefit from an increase in training data. Due to time constraints, this was not investigated in this experiment. However, this model may benefit more from additional data compared to similar machine learning models due to the removal of data, which causes the actual quantity of data the model is able to access to be considerably lower. Additional research to explore the relationship between this model and the amount of training data supplied could significantly improve the performance of the lexical extraction model.  
Ultimately, the results of this lexical extraction model suggest that the model in its current form does not significantly affect the accuracy of the text dating algorithm, but further research is necessary to draw a more conclusive result regarding its performance when paired with different methods of feature representation and classification. With additional investigation, this research could greatly improve the field of automated text dating and benefit human historians faced with this task.
